1. Rationale and hypotheses

The role of body size on species distribution has been a topic of continuous interest in macroecology, with the generally held trend that with greater body size also comes a larger range size (Brown and Maurer, 1989). This relationship may not be as straight forward with avian species, as small birds will have both small and large range sizes, which results in a more triangular shaped data distribution than a linear one when body size and range size (BSRS) are plotted together (Blackburn and Gaston, 1996). These authors went on to suggest that this triangular distribution may not hold true within taxa and there will instead be no clear and consistent BSRS relationship in avian species. However, Blackburn and Gaston (1996) only examined New World species, therefore we aim to examine the BSRS relationship at both a global scope and smaller taxonomic scales.

We will examine two taxonomic scales, the first on global avian scavengers as a single group, and the second by splitting the larger group into obligate scavengers and facultative scavengers. Obligate species will be defined as birds who feed exclusively on carrion, and we will select facultative scavengers by species in which carrion feeding is a commonly described foraging behaviour (BirdLife International, 2024). Obligate scavengers tend to be large-bodied birds (Ferguson-Lees, 2005), which we anticipate will have an effect on the BSRS trend for both objectives.

Hypothesis 1:

Our first objective seeks to identify a BSRS relationship across global avian scavengers and whether body size can be a predictor of the extent of occurrence (EOO) of a scavenger species. We expect to see a slightly negative relationship due to the number of obligate scavengers dominating the large body size classes that have small EOOs, because the extremeness of the large body size paired with the small EOOs of those obligate species may be enough to affect the linear relationship across all species, contrary to the expected relationship between bigger body sizes and larger EOOs (Brown and Maurer, 1989).

Hypothesis 2:

Our second objective asks whether there is a difference in the BSRS relationship between obligate and facultative scavengers. We anticipate that separating the obligate and facultative scavengers into their own groups will reveal different BSRS relationships. The range size of obligate scavengers will be limited by body size, because they are so large they must remain in geographic areas that facilitate flight, such as the Andean condor living in exclusively mountainous regions with strong updrafts. Therefore, we expect to see a negative relationship between BS and RS. However, facultative scavengers may show a positive body size-range size relationship that more closely matches the expectations outlined by Brown and Maurer (1989), because we are considering more species with a greater variability in body sizes.

3. Preliminary data exploration

When we look at the raw data, we see that small birds can have both small and large EOOs, but that EOO tends to be smaller as body size increases. It also appears that there may be more of an exponential relationship than a linear one, so logarithms would be useful here.

Plotting the data on a $log_{10}$ scale shows signs that scavengers as a whole do not seem to have a relationship between EOO and body size. When we consider obligates, however, there does seem to potentially be a negative linear relationship where larger obligate scavengers will have smaller range sizes. Facultative scavengers continue to seemingly not have a strong relationship between body size and range size, and/or have outliers.

Blackburn and Gaston (1996) suggest that a square root transformation for an area variable such as EOO might make more sense, but at the expense of comparing results with previous research. Since that is part of what Cara and I are doing, we will also not square root transform the EOO.

The above log-transformed histograms for "All scavengers" and "Facultative scavengers" look similar to Figure 1, C and D in Brown and Maurer (1989) when they reduced their spatial scale. Our histograms suggest a similar effect may be achieved by narrowing the taxonomic focus while maintaining a large geographic scale; in this case, a global one. "Obligate scavengers" looks more similar to when the spatial scale is highly restricted (Fig. 1; E, F), and have more larger-bodied species. This may be due to energetic constraints and diet, where animals with large body sizes can consume lower-quality food in greater quantities, and extract more nutrients with the higher-capacity digestive system (Brown and Maurer, 1989). And what's lower quality food than a literal corpse?

Normality test

It's more important that model residuals are normally distributed, but I should still see how the raw data is distributed.

In[165]:
# Make a list of columns for the Shapiro-Wilk tests
columns_to_test = [
    "Body size",
    "Extent of occurrence",
    "log Body size",
    "log Extent of occurrence",
]

# Make an empty dictionary
results = {}
for column in columns_to_test:
    shapiro_test = stats.shapiro(scavengers[column])
    # Populate the empty results dictionary
    results[column] = {
        "statistic": shapiro_test.statistic,
        "p_value": shapiro_test.pvalue,
    }

for column, result in results.items():
    print(
        f"{column} Shapiro-Wilk test:\n"
        f"Statistic: {result['statistic']:.2f}, p-value: {result['p_value']:.5f}\n"
    )

The Shapiro-Wilk test indicates that our data, even when log-transformed, is non-normal. The residuals from an OLS will therefore also likely be non-normal and violate some assumptions about linearity, but let's make some models and check.

4. Analyses

4.1 Global avian scavengers

4.1.1 Make the OLS model

Compare models with raw and log-transformed variables.

Define the variables

The design matrix, $X$, is handled differently between Python and R. Unlike in R, Python does not include the intercept term in the design matrix by default, which usually appears as a column of ones like in the following linear equation using matrix notation:

$$ \begin{equation} \begin{bmatrix} y_1 \cr y_2 \cr \vdots \cr y_n \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & x_1 \cr 1 & x_2 \cr \vdots & \vdots \cr 1 & x_n \end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix} \beta_0 \cr \beta_1 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} \epsilon_1 \cr \epsilon_2 \cr \vdots \cr \epsilon_n \end{bmatrix} \end{equation} $$

I therefore add the intercept with the add_constant function when I define my variables below (Statsmodels tools.add_constant; .pyTutorial, 2025).

In[10]:
# Define the X and Y matrices
y = scavengers["Extent of occurrence"]
x = scavengers["Body size"]
log_y = scavengers["log Extent of occurrence"]
log_x = scavengers["log Body size"]

# Add a column called "const" to the design matrix, X
x = sm.add_constant(x)
log_x = sm.add_constant(log_x)
x.head()

The coef column shows the OLS coefficients, from which we can determine the equation of our line as $y_i = 6.9554 + 0.0261x_i$, where $i$ is each observation in scavenger species.

These results tell us that for every increase in $log_{10}$ body size by one, there is a 0.03 increase in $log_{10}$ EOO. That is, for every tenfold increase in body size, there is a $10^{0.03} = 1.07$-fold increase in EOO.

This is practically a flat line, shown below in 4.1.1 Model plot, indicating that there is no relationship between body size and EOO across avian scavengers. We can infer from these results that no variation in EOO can be predicted by variation in body size and there is no relationship between the two ($R^2$ = <0.05, p-value = 0.863).

4.1.3 Residuals distribution

The Jarque-Bera test statistic from the model summary is quite large (9.479) and indicates that the residuals are not normally distributed, and the small Jarque-Bera p-value (p < 0.00874) says that there is a low probability of sampling from a normal distribution.

However, the Jarque-Bera test is better suited for larger sample sizes (SciPy User Guide, Jarque-Bera goodness of fit test), so let's assess the normality of the residuals with basic descriptive statistics and visualization.

The residuals are right-skewed without the log-transformation, because the mean ($5\cdot10^{-10}$) is greater than the median ($-8\cdot10^6$) and the median is closer to the bottom of the plot (Bobbit, 2021). The model would therefore be a good candidate for being log-transformed, shown on the right with more normally distributed residuals and also fewer potential outliers, so this may indeed be the better model.

Since the model seems to do better with a log transformation, I will make the remaining visuals using log_ols_model and investigate these potential outliers.

The residuals plot doesn't look too bad, though there may be an impact on the distribution through the lowermost values. The Q-Q plot is also not too bad, though there is a fair amount of departure from the quartiles line with the lower values, which may be due to those outliers shown in the box plot. Altogether, the visuals and Shapiro-Wilk test indicate that the residuals are not normally distributed, so OLS may not be the right choice of model as it assumes normally distributed residuals.

It's possible that when scavengers are examined as a single group there is not a linear relationship, not even one that can be teased out with a logarithmic transformation. This would align with what Blackburn and Gaston (1996) found with their study on New World birds. I could remove those observations, but I'm hesitant to delete data when the sample size is already small. Instead, let's try to manage the outliers.

De-weighting the outliers in the robust linear model had a negligible effect, with the line still at $7+0.03x_i$ after rounding, and p-value = 0.809 instead of 0.863.

4.1.5 GLM comparison

I want to compare my RLM result with that of a generalized linear model to see if it might either make a better fit or make more logical sense for the data I will not use a Gaussian distribution in the function's family argument, because that would be essentially the same test as the OLS and I already know that that model's residuals are non-normal. The families I will try:

  • Poisson
  • Tweedie
  • Gamma with a log link
  • Inverse Gaussian with a log link
In[57]:
# Redefine the X and Y matrices with non-transformed data
y = scavengers["Extent of occurrence"]
x = scavengers["Body size"]
x = sm.add_constant(x)

glm_model = sm.GLM(
    y, x, family=sm.families.Gamma(link=sm.families.links.Log())
).fit()

print(glm_model.summary())
print({f"AIC": glm_model.aic})

Based on the lowest Akaike's information criterion (AIC) score and log-likelihood scores, the GLM using a Gamma distribution with log link function is the best performing model. However, like the original OLS model, the low pseudo-$R^2$ value indicates that this model also does not explain much of the variability, and remains not statistically significant (p=0.245)

I cannot compare the OLS and the GLM models with AIC, because models using the same method log-likelihood estimation should be compared and Statsmodel's GLM uses iteratively reweighted least squares and OLS uses linear algebra (Cross Validated, Can AIC compare across different types of model?; Optimization - statsmodels 0.14.4, 2024).

4.1.6 Non-parametric test: Spearman's correlation coefficient

Assess the relationship instead with a Spearman correlation coefficient test from the SciPy library. This test is useful when data has violated assumptions of parametric tests, such as being non-normally distributed in our case (Field et al., 2012).

In[170]:
correlation, p_value = stats.spearmanr(
    scavengers["log Extent of occurrence"], scavengers["log Body size"]
)

print(f"Spearman correlation coefficient: {correlation}")
print(f"P-value: {p_value}")

Spearman correlation coefficient: 0.029723527660808546
P-value: 0.8141770084437394

Based on the above results for the Spearman correlation, the GLM, and the OLS, I see no reason to investigate global avian scavengers further and will conclude that there is not a compelling relationship between body size and EOO for global avian scavengers based on these data.

4.2 Obligate and facultative scavengers

4.2.1 Build the models

Now we want to determine whether there is a difference in the relationship between body size and range size between obligate and facultative scavengers that can be attributed to diet. We will do this by categorizing the birds as obligate or facultative carrion feeders and including an interaction term between the fixed effects, allowing Obligates and Facultative species to have their own intercepts and slopes (Greenwood, 2025). Adding an interaction term will make the linear equation look like:

$$ \begin{equation} y = \beta_0 + \beta_1x_1 + \beta_2x_2 + \beta_{12}x_1x_2 + \epsilon \tag{2} \end{equation} $$

We have two predictor variables, $x_1$ and $x_2$, for body size and diet. The first is quantitative data and the latter is categorical, which can be converted into numerical values by arbitrarily assigning a baseline group = 0 and the other = 1.

I could not find a nice way to do this with Statsmodels, so I got help from Copilot and imported Statsmodel's formulas API, which may look a little familiar to R users. GLM will be used going forward rather than OLS.

In[212]:
# Create new columns with spaceless names. I prefer camel case for screen reader reasons.
scavengers["logExtentOfOccurrence"] = scavengers["log Extent of occurrence"]
scavengers["logBodySize"] = scavengers["log Body size"]

formula = "logExtentOfOccurrence ~ logBodySize + Diet + logBodySize:Diet"
# NB: this is the same as writing "logExtentOfOccurrence ~ logBodySize * Diet", but I chose to write it like this to make the connection with Equation 2 more clear.

gaussian_interaction = smf.glm(formula=formula, data=scavengers).fit()
print(gaussian_interaction.summary())

I tried other families and using a Poisson distribution with a log link surprisingly indicated that there is a difference in the BSRS relationship between obligate and facultative scavengers. Let's compare these two models.

Despite being statistically significant, the Poisson GLM residuals look pretty awful. Therefore, I will reject that model in favour of the Gaussian GLM, even though it's not significant.

5. Significance

Contrary to our hypotheses, we found no evidence of a relationship between body size and EOO for global avian scavengers, and no difference in the BSRS relationship between obligate and facultative scavengers. These results highlight the importance of scale in macroecological research, showing how macroecological relationships can disintegrate when examined at smaller scales of spatial coverage, taxonomic inclusion, or feeding strategy. Limiting our focus to avian species with a scavenging strategy, even at a global extent, we have demonstrated that the BSRS relationship discussed in the seminal literature can fail to manifest (Brown and Maurer, 1989)
